re found to be minor for simulated mean$\backslash$nfields and scalar fluxes but are quite considerable for$\backslash$nvelocity and scalar variances. Neither changes in a$\backslash$nrather wide range of the domain size nor the horizontal$\backslash$ngrid resolution have any significant impact on the$\backslash$nsimulations. Although a rather strong sensitivity of$\backslash$nthe mean hydrometeor profiles and, consequently, cloud$\backslash$nfraction to the microphysics parameters is found, the$\backslash$neffects on the predicted mean temperature and humidity$\backslash$nprofiles are shown to be modest. It is found that the$\backslash$nspread among the time series of the simulated cloud$\backslash$nfraction, precipitable water, and surface precipitation$\backslash$nrate due to changes in the microphysics parameters is$\backslash$nwithin the uncertainty of the ensemble runs. This$\backslash$nsuggests that correlation of the CRM simulations to the$\backslash$nobserved long time series of the aforementioned$\backslash$nparameters cannot be generally used to validate the$\backslash$nmicrophysics scheme.},
