backslash$nppmv, in good agreement with $\backslash${\&}{\{}$\backslash${\#}{\}}8764;1.6 ppmv seen in HALOE data.$\backslash$nOn average, the Lagrangian calculations have a moist bias of $\backslash${\&}{\{}$\backslash${\#}{\}}8764;0.2$\backslash$nppmv, equivalent to a warm bias of the Lagrangian cold point of about$\backslash$n0.5 K. We conclude that the Lagrangian calculation based on synoptic-scale$\backslash$nvelocity and temperature fields yields estimates for stratospheric$\backslash$nwater vapor in good agreement with observations and that mesoscale$\backslash$nand cloud microphysical processes need not be invoked, at first order,$\backslash$nto explain annual mean and seasonal variation of water vapor mixing$\backslash$nratios in the tropical lower stratosphere.},
