@article{Turner1960,
abstract = { ABSTRACT In this paper it is shown how earlier results for buoyant$\backslash$nvortex rings may be extended to describe the corresponding two-dimensional$\backslash$ncase, which arises in the theory of bent-over plumes. It is again$\backslash$nassumed that in uniform surroundings the circulation remains constant$\backslash$nwhile the buoyancy acts to increase the momentum of the pair. The$\backslash$nbehaviour in two dimensions is quite different from that in three,$\backslash$nhowever; a buoyant vortex ring spreads linearly with height, whereas$\backslash$na buoyant pair spreads exponentially with height, or linearly with$\backslash$ntime (and therefore, in a bent-over plume, linearly with distance$\backslash$ndownwind).The theory has been extended to describe the rise of buoyant$\backslash$nrings and pairs through stably stratified surroundings having a linear$\backslash$ndensity gradient. The behaviour near the maximum height reached is$\backslash$nfound to depend critically in both cases on the relative rates at$\backslash$nwhich the circulation and the momentum fall to zero. If these reach$\backslash$nzero together, the rings or pairs will steadily increase in size$\backslash$nand come to rest at a finite height and with a finite radius. If$\backslash$nthe circulation is non-zero when the momentum vanishes, the radius$\backslash$nbegins to decrease soon after the buoyancy becomes zero, and the$\backslash$nvortices will therefore tend to break up suddenly and mix into their$\backslash$nsurroundings. There is a considerable increase in the final height$\backslash$nwhich should be attained by vortex rings or bentover plumes if the$\backslash$ninitial circulation is increased; it is suggested that releasing$\backslash$nsmoke intermittently, rather than continuously, at high velocity$\backslash$nmight be a means of increasing the effective height of chimneys in$\backslash$ncalm conditions. When the circulation reaches zero before the momentum$\backslash